ary casualties and a climate of violence and insecurity. In both cases the British were eventually and humiliatingly bailed out by the US army.In this thoughtful and compellingly readable book, Frank Ledwidge examines the British involvement in Iraq and Afghanistan, asking how and why it went so wrong. With the aid of copious research, interviews with senior officers, and his own personal experiences, he looks in detail at the failures of strategic thinking and culture that led to defeat in Britain's latest "small wars." This is an eye-opening analysis of the causes of military failure, and its enormous costs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfghan War, 2001-vPersonal narratives, British. 0aAfghan War, 2001-xCampaignsxAfghanistanxHelmand River Valley. 0aAfghan War, 2001-xCampaignszAfghanistanzHelmand River Valley. 0aAfghan War, 2001-xParticipation, British. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xCampaignsxIraqxBaṣrah. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xCampaignszIraqzBaṣrah. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xParticipation, British. 0aStrategic culturexGreat Britain. 0aStrategic culturezGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300180220423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300180220.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles